Describe the pattern between year and minimum mass of planet discovered using Radial Velocity.

Solution

## Solution
## Create the summary data frame
min_mass_df = planets %>%
  filter(method == "Radial Velocity") %>% 
  select(year, mass) %>%
  drop_na() %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(), min_mass = min(mass))

min_mass_df %>% 
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

ggplot(min_mass_df, aes(x = year, y = min_mass, size = n)) +
  geom_point() +

  xlab("Discovery Year") +

Solution

  • Here is a solution which uses mutate() to create a column with the total method counts and then uses filter() to retain the rows where the counts are 50 or more.
## Solution
## Use mutate() to add counts for each method and then filter on that column
methods_prop = planets %>% 
  group_by(method) %>% 
  mutate(method_count = n()) %>% 
  filter(method_count >= 50) %>% 
  count(year, method) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  mutate(total = sum(n),
         proportion = n / total) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(-total) %>%
  arrange(year)

methods_prop %>% 
  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

  • Yet another alternative solutions creates a summary data frame with method counts, filters for the common ones, and then uses semi_join() from next week’s lecture to filter the correct rows.
## Second solution
## Use the filtering join function semi_join() to keep rows which match one of the methods
methods_keep = planets %>% 
  count(method) %>% 
  filter(n >= 50)

methods_prop2 = planets %>% 
  ## filter to keep only commonly used methods
  semi_join(methods_keep, by = "method") %>% 
  ## the rest of the calculations
  count(year, method) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  mutate(total = sum(n),
         proportion = n / total) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(-total) %>%
  arrange(year)

  print(n = 10, width = Inf)

q5 = methods_prop %>%

  • 6b. The proportion of all days by month with positive precipitation.

Solution

## solution
official %>% 
  select(date, prcp) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(month = month(date, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(any_prcp = prcp > 0) %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            n_prcp = sum(any_prcp),
            p_prcp = n_prcp / n)

  • 6c. The average temperature (mean of tavg) by month for the years from 1991-2020. Consider these values to be the current normal mean temperatures. Then, find the average temperature by month in 2022. In how many months was the average temperature in 2022 higher than the normal mean temperature?
## Add your code here

[Type your answer here]

Solution

## solution
sol6c = official %>% 
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(year > 1990 & year != 2021) %>% 
  mutate(time = case_when(
    year < 2021 ~ "1991-2020",
    year == 2022 ~ "2022")) %>% 
  group_by(month, time) %>% 
  summarize(tavg = mean(tavg))

sol6c %>% 
  print(n = Inf)

Solution

## solution
official %>% 
  mutate(year = year(date)) %>% 
  select(date, year, tavg) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(tavg = mean(tavg)) %>% 
  slice_max(tavg, n = 10) %>% 
  mutate(recent = case_when(
    year >= 2000 ~ "this millenium",
    year < 2000 ~ "last millenium"))

Solution

prob7 = official %>% 
  filter(month(date) == 1) %>% 
  select(date, tavg) %>%

  group_by(year) %>%

2023 had the 8th warmest January in Madison history

  1. Make a plot which shows the average January temperature in Madison from 1869–2022. Add a smooth trend curve to the plot. Add a red dashed horizontal line at the mean temperature for 2023. Include meaningful axis labels and a title for the plot.

Solution

ggplot(prob7, aes(x = year, y = mean_tavg)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 27.02, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("January Avg. Temp (Deg. F)") +
  ggtitle("Mean January Temperature in Madison, Wisconsin",
          subtitle = "red line represents 2023, 27.02 deg F")
